DOI: 10.1097/FBP.0b013e32833c8544
Copyright © Lippincott Williams & Wilkins. Unauthorized reproduction of this article is prohibited.
cyclase-activating peptide and the growth hormone-releasing
hormone. The human Gip gene spans approximately 10 kb
and contains six exons encoding the pre-pro-GIP, a
153-amino acid peptide that is post-translationally pro-
cessed to the mature protein (42-amino acid). The exon–
intron structure of the GIP gene has been conserved within
mammals, although there was some variation in the rate of
protein sequence evolution for the peptide hormones
(Irwin, 2009). The amino acid sequence is highly conserved
among human, murine, porcine and bovine GIP sequences,
which exhibit more than 90% homology. Studies of human
Gip gene indicate that basal promoter activity is regulated
by cAMP-responsive elements (CREB) and contains
binding sites for Sp1, AP-1, AP-2 and other transcription
factors, whereas GATA-4, Isl-1 and Pdx-1 binds to
the rodent GIP promoter (Baggio and Drucker, 2007;
Jepeal et al., 2008). However, the molecular mechanisms
controlling the GIP expression have not been fully
elucidated to date.
GIP immunoreactivity has been primarily localized in the
endocrine K cells from porcine, rodent and human in-
testinal tissues (Buchan et al., 1978; Mortensen et al.,
2003). Further demonstrations of GIP protein or mRNA
expression were performed in human and rodent duode-
num, jejunum, stomach and sub-mandibular salivary gland
(Buchan et al., 1978; Tseng et al., 1993; Yeung et al., 1999;
Messenger et al., 2003). Recently, the GIP expression and
secretion were confirmed in pancreatic a-cells, suggesting
its contribution for maintaining the glucose-stimulated
insulin secretion (Fujita et al., 2010).
Furthermore, several established lines of tumoral cells
(including those from intestinal, salivary, and endocrine
origins) were screened for the expression of GIP mRNA,
but only STC-1 cells (derived from a mouse neuroendo-
crine tumor) express high levels of GIP mRNA (Boylan
et al., 1997). Despite the above evidence obtained in cul-
tured cells, until recently, there was no further evidence
of GIP-like immunoreactivity in nerve circuits of the
intestinal tract (Polak et al., 1977). However, a recent
analysis of hippocampal gene expression using a cDNA
array strategy identified the Gip gene, whose expression
varied strongly in parallel with cell-proliferation rates
(Nyberg et al., 2005). The same research group detected a
strong GIP immunoreactivity in the olfactory bulb,
hippocampus and Purkinje cells in the cerebellum of
adult rats (Nyberg et al., 2007). GIP appears to be mainly
neuronal in its distribution, as GIP immunoreactivity was
frequently found to co-localize with neuronal but never
with glial markers (Nyberg et al., 2007).
The glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide receptor
The GIPR was initially cloned from a rat insulinoma cell line
(Usdin et al., 1993), and then, from the other human and
rodent sources (Gremlich et al., 1995; Volz et al., 1995;
Wheeler et al., 1995). The human Gipr gene is composed of
14 exons and contains a 1398bp open reading frame coding a
466-amino acid protein (B50kDa). Aside from the 30UTR
found in the rat Gipr, human and rat genes are identical in
structure. Moreover, the human protein sequence is 81%
identical to that of the rat GIPR. As a member of the class B
seven-transmembrane domain G-protein coupled receptor
(GPCR) family, GIPR has the highest homology (B40%)
with other members of this GPCR family: the glucagon and
the GLP-1 receptors (Gremlich et al., 1995).
In rats, GIPR mRNA is expressed not only in pancreatic
b-cells, but also in various other tissues, including the
gut, heart, adipose tissue, inner layers of adrenal gland,
pituitary and brain, whereas it is not found in kidney,
spleen, or liver (Usdin et al., 1993). Regarding brain regions,
GIPR transcripts were found in the cerebral cortex, hippo-
campus, and olfactory bulb (Usdin et al., 1993). Moreover,
recent immunohistochemical analyses performed by our
group revealed abundant GIPR staining in neurons and less
markedly in glial cells of cortical and subcortical rat brain
structures (Fig. 1). The CA1, CA2 and CA3 pyramidal cells
(Fig. 1a), dentate gyrus (DG) granular cells (Fig. 1a) of the
hippocampal formation and the cells of the subventricular
zone (SVZ) (Fig. 1c) revealed substantial staining for GIPR
protein expression, which was also observed in cerebellum,
cerebral cortex, substantia nigra, olfactory tubercle, striatum,
thalamic nuclei (data not shown). Moreover, Gipr gene and
GIPR protein were detected in the DG granular cell layer
and adult hippocampal progenitor cells of rats (Nyberg et al.,
2005). In human adult tissues, GIPR mRNA is expressed
in the normal pancreas, trachea, brain, heart, gut, spleen,
thymus, blood cells, lung, kidney and bone; in human fetal
tissues, it was found in the lung, heart and kidney (Gremlich
et al., 1995; Bollag et al., 2000; Baldacchino et al., 2005). Of
note, the presence of GIPR immunoreactivity in human brain
was recently shown by our group (Fig. 4), and further details
of these findings will be addressed in the next sections.
Biological effects of glucose-dependent
insulinotropic polypeptide
Glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide in the
periphery: regulation of insulin release and nonpancreatic
effects
GIP is mostly studied for its role in regulating post-
prandial insulin release by pancreatic b-cells (Baggio and
Drucker, 2007). Although the GIP synthesis and secretion
by the gut are under the control of nutrients, mainly
glucose, the action of GIP on GIPR in the pancreatic b-
cells is not dependent on glucose. However, high glucose
concentration may actually down-regulate the GIPR
through a decrease in the PPAR-a transcription, which
would maintain the basal level of GIPR expression (Lynn
et al., 2003). As a consequence of GIP binding, the GIPR
activates adenylyl cyclase, increasing cAMP production,
and ultimately leads to the inhibition of KATP channel,
elevation of intracellular Ca2 + and insulin exocytosis (Lu
et al., 1993; Volz et al., 1995). Recent studies investigating
intracellular pathways suggest that GIP exerts its effects
Role of GIPR in the central nervous system Figueiredo et al.
395
Copyright © Lippincott Williams & Wilkins. Unauthorized reproduction of this article is prohibited.
through PLA2 pathways and activation of MAP kinases
and a number of other enzymatic pathways modulate its
effects in b-cell responses, including CREB, Rap1/Raf-A/
Mek/Erk1/2 and PI3K/PKB/Foxo1 (Trumper et al., 2001;
Ehses et al., 2003; Kim et al., 2005). GIP may also
contribute to the growth, differentiation and survival of
b-cells (Kubota et al., 1997; Trumper et al., 2001).
The GIPRs also have biological effects on nonpancreatic
tissues. In bone tissues, GIP has anabolic effects on
osteoblasts and osteoclasts in vitro, although the acute
administration of GIP does not seem to alter bone turnover
in humans (Baggio and Drucker, 2007). In adipocytes,
GIP regulates accumulation of dietary fat (Flatt, 2008). In
adult rat hippocampus, GIP exerts a regulatory function
in progenitor cell proliferation (Nyberg et al., 2005). The
study of GIPR knockout mice revealed a surprisingly
modest phenotype, with reduced levels of glucose-stimu-
lated insulin secretion and resistance to diet-induced
obesity (Hansotia and Drucker, 2005), while other con-
clusions about a blunted GIP effect in bone, adipose tissue
and the CNS require additional analysis of GIPR – / –
mice. More evidence of nonpancreatic GIPR function is
related to adrenal cell proliferation and tumorigenesis
(Mazzuco et al., 2006), and GIP-dependent over-secretion
of cortisol or aldosterone by adrenal tumors (Lampron
et al., 2009; Mazzuco et al., 2010).
Glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide
in the central nervous system: neuroplasticity
Considering that oscillations in blood glucose concentra-
tions and insulin signaling affect the neuronal activity, it
is tempting to imagine that GIP and its receptor would
have an impact on neuronal function. Recent studies have
considered this possibility and found that manipulation of
the GIPR indeed alters the neuronal plasticity. Activation
of GIPR by GIP itself or by a stable analog N-AcGIP
facilitated the induction of long-term potentiation (LTP)
in hippocampus slices, using a weak stimulation protocol.
In contrast, the blockade of these receptors by the
antagonist Pro(3)GIP reduced LTP obtained with a strong
induction protocol in the same preparation (Gault and
Holscher, 2008b).
These findings have shown that the manipulation of GIP
signaling induces a profound impact on neuronal plasticity
(Gault and Holscher, 2008b). The LTP increment pro-
voked by the activation of GIPR is putatively because of
the modulation of vesicle release at the presynaptic termi-
nal, as GIP does not alter the basic transmission or electrical
properties of neurons, but rather influences the induction
of LTP after high-frequency stimulation. Mechanisms of
vesicular neurotransmitter release, mediated by Ca2 +,
operate in neurons (Winder and Conn, 1993; Okamoto
et al., 1994; Wheeler et al., 1994). Besides GIP, the GLP-1
incretin also modulates the glutamate-induced Ca2 +
influx, activates PKA and MAP kinases (Gilman et al.,
2003) and modulates the release of neurotransmitters in
neurons, affecting the LTP induction in the hippocampus
(Gispen and Biessels, 2000; Li and Holscher, 2007).
Glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide
in the central nervous system: neurogenesis
Generation of newly born neurons in the adult brain is a
relatively recent research topic and the overall concept
resides in that some brain areas surrounding the lateral
