ventricle contain stem cells that give rise to defined
subsets of neurons (Gage, 2000; Merkle et al., 2007). The
stem cells differentiate to neuronal precursors maintain-
ing an immature migratory state until their arrival in the
respective target structures (Boutin et al., 2010). The main
neurogenic sites in the adult brain are the SVZ and the
DG of the hippocampal formation, whose neural stem cells
produce progenitors that migrate towards their ultimate
location: the olfactory bulb and granular cell layer of the
DG, respectively (Luskin, 1993; Lois and Alvarez-Buylla,
1994; Doetsch et al., 1997; Gage, 2000; Cayre et al., 2009).
The gastrointestinal regulatory polypeptides, such as
vasoactive intestinal peptide, secretin and glucagon are
broadly distributed in the brain (Sims et al., 1980; Jin
et al., 1988; Masuo et al., 1993a, 1993b; Hannibal, 2002)
and have several functions within the CNS, such as neuro-
modulation, brain development, cell-cycle regulation,
differentiation, and cell death (Sherwood et al., 2000)
that may putatively be shared by GIP, as a member of this
gastrointestinal regulatory polypeptides superfamily.
For instance, GIP may also be involved in mechanisms of
neuronal protection (Holscher and Li, 2008; Gault and
Holscher, 2008a, 2008b; Buhren et al., 2009) and neuro-
genesis (Nyberg et al., 2005). The first description of the
possible role of GIP in neuroplasticity is quite recent
(Nyberg et al., 2005). Both the GIP and GIPR are mark-
edly expressed in neurons of the DG of hippocampus, and
its up-regulation is associated with increased rates of
neuronal proliferation (Nyberg et al., 2005). In fact, GIPR
knockout mice have less than half of the number of new
proliferating cells in the hippocampus compared to wild-
types (Nyberg et al., 2005). Furthermore, GIP acts as a growth
factor for b-cells (Trumper et al., 2001) and stimulates the
axonal regeneration after nerve crush (Buhren et al., 2009).
Regarding the hippocampus, recent experimental evidence
from our group is in line with possible effects of GIP and its
receptor in adult neurogenesis. We used physical exercise,
a commonly used environmental manipulation that stimu-
lates hippocampal neurogenesis (van Praag et al., 1999;
Cotman and Berchtold, 2002; Schmidt-Hieber et al., 2004),
to investigate the expression of GIPR in the rat DG, known
as an area of active neurogenesis in the adult brain. As
expected, we found an increase in both the cellular pro-
liferation (number of KI-67-positive cells) (Fig. 2d) and
GIPR expression (Fig. 2b and c) in the DG of aged rats
after a chronic running exercise. Exercised aged rats also
displayed higher GIPR staining in the hippocampus (Fig. 2b
and c) and improved spatial memory in the water maze
paradigm (Fig 2e). These findings suggest that this gut-
released peptide regulates structural and functional
changes that support hippocampus plasticity.
Glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide in the
central nervous system: behavioral effects
Evidence of the impact of GIP on animal behavior is so
recent that it basically comes from one study investigating
the behavior of transgenic mice that over-express GIP
(Ding et al., 2006). This transgenic mouse line was con-
structed under the control of a heavy metal-inducible
promoter that induced the over-expression of GIP to levels
five-to-six times higher than controls. Curiously, even at base-
line, before heavy metal ingestion, the transgenic mice had
more than two-fold higher serum levels of GIP than control
mice (Ding et al., 2006). Because the sustained elevation
of GIP to such high levels resulted in downregulation of
GIPR, the transgenic mice were tested in a series of
behavioral tasks under baseline conditions (i.e. twice the
regular GIP expression). The mice were tested in the elevated
plus-maze and light/dark box for anxiety, in the open-field
and rotarod for locomotion and motor coordination, in the
hot-plate and tail-flick for sensorimotor response, and in the
Y-maze and object recognition for cognition. The findings
obtained with these animals suggested that GIP over-
expression did not alter anxiety-like behavior, as measured
by the time spent in the open arms of the elevated plus-
maze or the time in the light compartment of the dark/light
box and did not alter nociceptive responses in the tail-flick
and hot-plate tests. However, the over-expression of GIP
improved motor performance in the open-field and rotarod
tests and improved short-term spatial memory (without
altering the spontaneous alteration) in the Y-maze test
(Ding et al., 2006). Collectively, these results suggest that
GIP over-expression improves hippocampus-dependent
spatial memory, but maintains regular working memory per-
formance (Ding et al., 2006). Unfortunately, knockout mice
for GIP or GIPR, although already available, have not yet
been tested in behavioral tasks (Nyberg et al., 2005).
Unpublished results from our group have indicated that
the intracerebroventricular (i.c.v.) injection of GIP (0.5–
2 nmol) did not alter the spatial memory of the adult Swiss
mice evaluated in the water maze task.
Role of glucose-dependent insulinotropic
polypeptide in neurological disorders
The previous section presented the evidence suggesting
that the physiological role of GIP is far wider than con-
sidered before and that studies in the field should not con-
tinue to be restricted to the investigation of GIP effects on
pancreatic cells and insulin release. As an effort to illustrate
the potential of the GIP system as an innovative target for
future pharmacotherapies, the next sections depict the role
of GIP in the pathophysiology of some experimental models
of neurological diseases, such as epilepsy, PD and AD.
Mesial temporal lobe epilepsy
Epilepsy is a mental health problem with a prevalence of
5–10 cases per 1000 inhabitants in developed countries
(Hauser et al., 1998; Wiebe et al., 2001). Epilepsies are the
second most common cause of mental health disability,
particularly among young adults (Murray et al., 1994).
More than 40 recognized epileptic syndromes are already
known, characterized by paroxysmal episodes of brain
