dysfunction leading to recurrent stereotyped behavioral
alterations, termed seizures (Schwartkroin and McIntyre,
1997). The epileptic attack results from the abnormal
hyperexcitability and hypersynchrony of neuronal popu-
lations (Hauser et al., 1998). The development of abnor-
mal brain tissue containing the ‘hyperexcitable epileptic
neurons’ strategically connected through the ‘epileptic
network’ is called epileptogenesis (Walz et al., 2002). Epi-
leptogenesis is a complex process and frequently results
from the interaction of genetic and environmental factors.
The possible role of GIP in the context of epileptogenesis
started to be investigated very recently. Our preliminary
findings suggest that GIPR may be involved in the patho-
physiology of mesial temporal lobe epilepsy related to
hippocampus sclerosis (MTLE-HS). Patients usually have
a previous history of an initial precipitating injury such as
a febrile seizure, prolonged seizure, trauma, or intracranial
infections in childhood. The recurrent epileptic attacks
start in the second decade of life and frequently become
refractory to pharmacological treatment (Engel, 1996).
The MTLE-HS represents around 70% of surgically-treated
cases of the worldwide specialized epilepsy centers
(Engel, 1996; Wiebe et al., 2001). In the pilocarpine animal
model, a prolonged status epilepticus induced by systemic
pilocarpine (Pilo-SE) causes neuronal loss, synaptic reorga-
nization, mossy fiber sprouting in hippocampus and spon-
taneous recurrent seizures similar to MTLE-HS in
humans (Cavalheiro et al., 1991; Walz et al., 1999; Bonan
et al., 2000). The acute phase of the model (like the
initial precipitating injury in humans) includes excitatory
glutamatergic transmission (Cavalheiro et al., 1991),
oxidative stress (Dal-Pizzol et al., 2000) and apoptosis.
After a ‘silent’ period of 5–45 days (mean 14 ± 3 days),
animals start to show spontaneous epileptic seizures. In
the chronic period, epileptic animals have an increased
number of ‘intrinsically-bursting’ cells in the CA1 region of
the hippocampus (47% of CA1 neurons) in comparison
with controls (only 3%). Some of these neurons (about
10%) develop spontaneous bursts, which are not observed
in controls (Sanabria et al., 2001). The same investigators
showed a higher proportion of bursting neurons distributed
in layer V (60%) of the neocortex of epileptic rats compared
with 22% in control slices (Sanabria et al., 2002).
Under the normal conditions, there is a high expression of
GIPR in the DG of the hippocampus, followed by the
CA1, CA2, CA3 regions and cortex (Fig. 1a). Recently, we
showed a time-dependent and region-dependent increase
of GIPR expression in the hippocampus and neocortex of
rats submitted to the pilocarpine model (Figueiredo et al.
unpublished results). After the Pilo-SE induction, expres-
sion of GIPR increases in the hippocampus 1 h, evolving
to a slight reduction 12 h later, followed by a second
‘wave’ of increased expression 5 days after Pilo-SE. In the
cortex, expression of GIPR consistently increases 1 h, 12 h
and 5 days after the Pilo-SE. In all these regions, GIPR
expression returns almost to the baseline 50 days after
Pilo-SE (Table 1 and Fig. 3).
The increase in the GIPR expression from the basal level
was more prominent in CA2, followed by CA1, CA3, DG
and neocortex (Table 1 and Fig. 3). The increase in GIPR
expression in the DG may be associated with the neuro-
genesis observed after prolonged Pilo-SE (Parent, 2003)
and with the epileptogenesis process (Walter et al., 2007).
Considering that GIPR activation positively modulates
LTP in the CA1 region of hippocampus (Gault and Holscher,
2008b), the early increase of GIPR expression in the hip-
pocampus and neocortex induced by Pilo-SE may reflect
the occurrence of plastic electrophysiological alterations
within hippocampal neurons (Sanabria et al., 2002).
The expression of GIPR was inversely proportional to the
intensity of Fluoro-Jade staining, a marker of neuronal
degeneration, suggesting an association between GIPR
expression and neuronal survival in the experimentally-
induced hippocampal sclerosis (Figueiredo et al., unpub-
lished results). In accordance, earlier studies showed that
GIP/GIPR are implicated with the recovery of peripheral
nerve lesion (Buhren et al., 2009). A consistent cause-effect
relation between GIPR and neuroprotection remains to be
proven, but our findings indicate an association between
the GIPR expression and neuronal survival in the Pilo-SE
model. The precise role of GIPR in the neuroprotection/
neuroplasticity events related to epileptogenesis deserves
further investigation. Considering the importance of GIPR
with the metabolic regulation, we also speculate its
participation in the regulation of brain energetic balance
during the critical phase of the status epilepticus.
In a complementary approach, we investigated, for the
first time, the GIPR expression in the hippocampus and
neocortex of four patients with MTLE-HS. The qualita-
tive analysis of the GIPR expression pattern observed in
the hippocampus and neocortex was similar to that
observed in the animals submitted chronically to Pilo-SE.
