intracytoplasmic, proteinaceous inclusions, termed Lewy
bodies and dystrophic Lewy neuritis, in surviving neurons
(Hirsch et al., 1988). However, additional neuronal fields
and neurotransmitter systems are also involved in PD,
including the locus coeruleus, dorsal motor nucleus,
substantia innominata, autonomic nervous system and
cerebral cortex (Braak et al., 2004). Accordingly, choliner-
gic, adrenergic and serotoninergic neurons are also
degenerated, which seems to be responsible for the
nonmotor symptoms of PD encompassing olfactory and
memory impairments, sleep abnormalities and depres-
sion, as well as gastrointestinal disturbance, which
precede the classical motor symptoms (Chaudhuri et al.,
2006).
Dopamine-replacement therapy has dominated the treat-
ment of PD since the early 1960’s and although the cur-
rently approved anti-parkinsonian agents offer effective
relief of the motor deficits, especially in the early/moderate
stages of the disease, they do not alleviate the underlying
dopaminergic neurodegeneration and drug efficacy is
gradually lost (Allain et al., 2008). Moreover, another major
limitation of chronic dopaminergic therapy is the numerous
adverse effects, such as development of abnormal invol-
untary movements (namely dyskinesia), psychosis and
behavioral disturbances (e.g. compulsive gambling, hyper-
sexuality) (Ahlskog and Muenter, 2001). Additionally,
nonmotor features of PD invariably do not respond to
dopaminergic medication and probably form the major
current challenge faced in the clinical management of
PD (Chaudhuri et al., 2006). The three main strategic
developments that have led to progress in the medical
management of PD have focused on improvements in
dopaminergic therapies, (including those aimed at mana-
ging or preventing the onset of motor complications), the
identification of nondopaminergic drugs for symptomatic
improvement, and the discovery of compounds to modify
the course of PD (Schapira et al., 2006).
The definition of neuroprotection in PD is complex and
involves the potential for preventing cell death and
restoring function to damaged neurons, as well as increasing
neuronal number (Schapira, 2004). The development of
drugs to slow or prevent the progression of PD might
logically evolve from an improved understanding of the
etiology and pathogenesis of PD. There have certainly
been major advances in these areas over the past few
years and the prospect for the introduction of ‘neuropro-
tective’ therapies is much improved. However, no drug
has yet been shown to be neuroprotective in PD, although
several have already been tested in clinical trials. The
potential neuroprotective drugs include dopamine agonists
and monoamine oxidase type B inhibitors, although
others, including co-enzyme Q10, growth factors, anti-
apoptotic agents and glutamate inhibitors, have also been
the subjects of clinical trials in PD (Schapira et al., 2006).
Although the etiology of PD is presently unknown,
epidemiological studies have indicated that its incidence
appears to be higher in persons with type 2 diabetes
mellitus, suggesting that shared mechanisms, such as insulin
dysregulation, may underlie these conditions (Craft and
