(Baggio and Drucker, 2007; Lee and Pervaiz, 2007), one
of many commonalities shared by these degenerative
conditions.
Both GIP and GLP-1 incretins or their novel enzyme-
resistant analogs (N-AcGIP and exendin-4, EX-4, respec-
tively) induce numerous biological actions in the pancreas,
including glucose homeostasis regulation, insulin release,
and, notably, b-cell proliferation and inhibition of apoptosis
(Li et al., 2003; Baggio and Drucker, 2007). N-AcGIP has
some effects on synaptic plasticity (see the next section),
while the currently available anti-diabetic drug EX-4
displays neurotrophic (Perry et al., 2002b) and neuropro-
tective (Perry et al., 2002a) properties in cultured PC12
cells subjected to excitotoxic stress. EX-4 restores choline
acetyl transferase positive cells following ibotenic acid
lesions (Perry et al., 2002a). These observations have led
some investigators to suggest that stimulation of GLP-1
receptors (GLP-1R) could be a therapeutic option in
neurodegenerative disorders such as PD. Interestingly,
i.c.v. pretreatment with EX-4 (20 nmol, 0.25 ml/h over
7 days) provided a complete protection against the 1-
methyl-4-phenyl-1,2,3,6-tetrahydropyridine (MPTP)-in-
duced dopamine cell death in the SNpc of mice, through
anti-apoptotic mechanisms (Li et al., 2003). More-
over, other studies demonstrated that EX-4 induces
neurogenesis of neural stem cells, both in culture and
in the SVZ of rats submitted to the 6-hydroxydopamine
(6-OHDA) experimental model of PD (Bertilsson et al.,
2008; Harkavyi et al., 2008). The parallel GLP-1R-
mediated trophic and protective actions of EX-4 in
neurons may be of clinical utility in the treatment of
chronic neurological disorders such as PD.
On the other hand, epidemiological and experimental
studies suggest that exposure to several environmental
agents, including agricultural chemicals, may contribute
to the pathogenesis of PD (Gorell et al., 1998). Some-
times such agents may enter the brain through the
olfactory neuroepithelium, a concept termed the ‘olfac-
tory vector hypothesis’ (Doty, 2008). Consistent with this
suggestion, we have recently proposed a new experi-
mental model of PD consisting of a single intranasal (i.n.)
administration of MPTP in rats (Prediger et al., 2006,
2009) and mice (Prediger et al., 2010). Rodents treated
i.n. with MPTP suffer progressive impairments in olfactory,
cognitive, and motor functions associated with time-
dependent disruption of dopaminergic neurotransmission
in different brain structures, conceivably analogous to
those observed during different stages of PD (Chaudhuri
et al., 2006). The behavioral impairments induced by i.n.
MPTP administration are associated, at least in part, with
alterations in brain antioxidant status and lipid peroxida-
tion (Franco et al., 2007), neuroinflammation (Rojo et al.,
2006) and apoptotic cell death mechanisms (Prediger
et al., 2009, 2010).
As can be seen in Fig. 5a, at 21 days after a single bilateral
i.n. administration of MPTP 1 mg/nostril; for more details
see (Prediger et al., 2006), the rats receiving MPTP showed
classic reductions in the number of tyrosine hydroxylase-
immunoreactive cells, a marker of dopaminergic cells, in
the SNpc. MPTP-treated rats also displayed motor impair-
ments, as assessed in the rotarod and open-field tests,
that started at 14 days after i.n. MPTP administration
(data not shown). Interestingly, the i.n. infusion of MPTP
seems to increase the GIPR expression in the SNpc of
rats as evidenced by immunostaining (Fig. 5b and c). This
constitutes the first evidence suggesting that GIP (as
previously showed for GLP-1) and its receptor might play
a critical role in the dopaminergic neurodegeneration
observed in the SNpc of MPTP-treated rodents. There-
fore, it is possible that GIP (through the activation of
GIPR in the SNpc) is instigating de novo neurogenesis,
presumably from recruited stem cells, as has been post-
ulated in other studies for EX-4 and GLP-1R (Harkavyi
et al., 2008).
Alzheimer’s disease
AD is the most common form of dementia, accounting for
50–60% of all cases, nearly 20 million affected individuals
worldwide (Blennow et al., 2006). The prevalence of AD
is below 1% in individuals aged less than 65 years, but it
increases to approximately 25% of the individuals aged
85 years or older in the western world (Ferri et al., 2005).
This neurodegenerative disease is associated with pro-
gressive and permanent decline in memory and overall
cognitive abilities and is so impairing that it tends to
reduce the post-diagnosis lifespan to nearly half the dura-
tion of a nondemented elderly person (Larson et al., 2004).
The first cognitive function affected is the episodic
memory (Artero et al., 2003), but during the progression
of the disease, attention, executive functions, semantic
memory, spatial orientation and even language begin to
deteriorate (Lambon Ralph et al., 2003).
The examination of post-mortem brains of AD patients
defined that the histopathological hallmarks of the disease
are the formation of senile plaques and neurofibrillary
tangles, which are mainly formed due to deposition of
b-amyloid (Ab) peptides and the hyperphosphorylated
tau protein, respectively (Cotman and Su, 1996). The
main deposition sites of the Ab peptides and tau proteins
in the diseased brain are the neocortex and hippocampus
(Taguchi et al., 2005). Moreover, recent evidence suggests
an inflammatory component in AD, including astrogliosis,
microgliosis and elevation of pro-inflammatory cytokines
402
Behavioural Pharmacology
2010, Vol 21 No 5&6
Copyright © Lippincott Williams & Wilkins. Unauthorized reproduction of this article is prohibited.
(Wyss-Coray, 2006) that triggers a cascade of events
culminating in synaptic dysfunction, synaptic degenera-
tion and eventual neuronal death (Walsh and Selkoe,
2004).
The Ab peptides are formed upon proteolytic cleavage of
the amyloid precursor protein (APP) by b and g-secretases
(Haass and De Strooper, 1999). APP processing by
secretase enzymes occurs in two distinct pathways, the
