nonamyloidogenic and amyloidogenic pathways. Soluble
APP is cleaved by a-secretase and b-secretase to release
the a and b soluble forms of the APP (De Strooper et al.,
1993). In the nonamyloidogenic pathway g-secretase
cleavage of the C-terminal fragment releases a non-
amyloidogenic peptide, whereas in the amyloidogenic
pathway, the g-secretase enzyme releases the Ab peptides
(De Strooper et al., 1993). The peptides formed by the
amyloidogenic pathway may differ in size, with Ab(1–40)
and Ab(1–42) being the most frequent forms. Both are
toxic peptides that aggregate into amyloid plaques
(Kirkitadze and Kowalska, 2005). The prior knowledge
