about these Ab peptides in the brain of AD patients was
the foundation for the development of one of the most
popular animal models of AD. The impairment of
cognitive functions and progressive neurodegeneration
induced by Ab peptides in rodents are consistently
studied as animal models of AD. Cognitive deficits have
been documented in both transgenic mice over-expressing
mutant human APP (Hsiao et al., 1996; Arendash et al.,
2004) and following central administration of the synthetic
Ab(1–40) (Flood et al., 1991; Medeiros et al., 2007;
Prediger et al., 2007), Ab(1–42) (Terranova et al., 1996;
Wirth et al., 1999; Jhoo et al., 2004) peptides, or the
smaller fragment Ab(25–35), which also elicits biological
effects (Holscher et al., 2007; Gault and Holscher, 2008a).
Electrophysiological studies have also found that the i.c.v.
infusion of Ab peptides reduces the in-vivo induction of
LTP in the hippocampus in a precise time-course (Freir
et al., 2001; Gengler et al., 2007), while impairing the
spatial memory ability of mice (Holscher et al., 2007).
The aforementioned effects of GIP on cellular prolifera-
tion and neuronal plasticity among others, and the
expression of this incretin peptide and its receptor in
the hippocampus (Nyberg et al., 2005, 2007) suggests a
putative role of GIP against the neurotoxic effects of Ab
peptides in the rodent brain. Recently, the investigation
of the modulation of GIPR on the impairing effects of Ab
peptides on hippocampal LTP was carried out (Gault and
Holscher, 2008b). The experimental approach consisted
in the i.c.v. injection of the synthetic GIP analogue N-
AcGIP in rats, together with the in-vivo induction of LTP
in the perforant path of the hippocampus, registered with
electrodes placed in the CA1 area. Confirming previous
studies, Ab(25–35) peptide impaired the induction of
LTP compared to a control group injected with an
inactive scramble Ab(25–35) peptide sequence. Injection
of N-AcGIP completely reversed the effects of the
Ab(25–35) peptide. Complementary to this approach,
we investigated the effects of GIP on learning and
memory abilities of Ab(1–40)-injected mice. The mem-
ory task chosen was the water maze spatial reference task,
consisting of a 10-trials training to find a submerged
platform (max 60 s), followed 24 h later by a 60-s spatial
memory ‘probe’ test, where the platform was absent. The
mice used spatial visual cues to navigate in the water maze
and find the hidden platform (for more details of the pro-
cedure, see Medeiros et al., 2007; Prediger et al., 2007). As
can be seen in Fig. 6a, a single i.c.v. infusion of Ab(1–40)
(400 pmol/mouse) led to a severe impairment of spatial
learning in the water maze task during the training
session, resulting in a deficit of spatial memory in the test,
as assessed by the latency to the platform location and
percentage in the target quadrant (Fig. 6c and d). Both
learning and memory impairments induced by Ab(1–40)
injection were abolished by the co-administration of GIP.
No group difference concerning the swim speed was
found (Fig. 6b). The underlying mechanisms of the Ab
peptides-detrimental effects on LTP probably include
the increase of K +-channel activity (Jalonen et al., 1997),
reduction of voltage-gated Ca2 + channels activity and
Ca2 + influx (Abe and Kimura, 1996), which in turn affect
Ca2 +-sensitive enzymes and reduce vesicular neuro-
transmitter release (Harris et al., 2004).
Interestingly, the effects of Ab peptides are also reduced
by another incretin, GLP-1 (Perry et al., 2003). Stimula-
tion of the GLP-1 receptor induces neurite growth and
protects against excitotoxic cell death and oxidative
injury in cultured neuronal cells, likely because of control
of Ca2 + influx into neurons (Perry et al., 2003) and
consequent modulation of transmitter release. Injection
of GLP-1 by the i.c.v. route increases the release of
glutamate and the spontaneous firing rate of hippocampal
neurons in vivo (Mora et al., 1992; Oka et al., 1999). This
electrophysiological alteration has an impact on behavior,
as acute injection of a stable analog of GLP-1 prevents the
memory impairment induced by Ab peptides (Oka et al.,
1999). This incretin also increases cell proliferation and
neuronal regeneration in animal models, which may help
prevent or reduce long-term damage induced by neuro-
degeneration and Ab plaque-induced gliosis (Perry et al.,
2003; Perry and Greig, 2005). Altogether, these results
suggest that the incretins, such as GIP and GLP-1, affect
neuronal activity directly, but also through improvement
of neuronal viability. We suggest the incretin receptors as
a new therapeutic opportunity to counteract neurotoxic
effects of Ab fragments by reducing excitotoxicity and,
theoretically, as a possibility to improve neuronal main-
tenance and replacement, regaining lost cognitive func-
tions in AD patients.
Discussion
This article reviews the recent evidence that the incretin
peptide GIP plays an important role not only as a
modulator of insulin release by the pancreatic b-cells, but
fundamentally as an important factor for neuronal plasticity,
growth and survival in the CNS. Possible therapeutic
opportunities for neurological disorders through the
modulation of GIPR are pointed out, in the expectancy
that this review may inspire clinical researchers and foster
experimental approaches using GIP as the therapeutic
target. We took the first step towards a better compre-
hension of the role of GIP in the human brain by
identifying the expression of GIPR in hippocampal slices
of epileptic patients. Since apoptotic cell death has
been identified as one of the main molecular processes
associated with the neurological disorders here presented,
future therapeutic strategies could target the use of com-
pounds able to prevent the occurrence of apoptosis.
Alternatively, a positive therapeutic effect could be pro-
duced by molecules with neurotrophic properties, with
the ability to stimulate neurogenesis and/or maintain
the
integrity
of
the
existent
cells.
Manipulation
of the neuronal incretins (such as GIP) beckons as an
